Section 1: Problem Statement - Bike Share in Vancouver

The industry of bike sharing, which has just emerged in recent years with the rapid development of sharing-economy, refers to the bike sharing service provided by enterprises on campus, subway station, bus station, residential area, commercial area and other public service area. It’s not only a time-sharing lease mode but also a new type of green environmental protection sharing economy. In addition, bike sharing is essentially a new type of vehicle rental business - bicycle rental business, which relies mainly on cycling bicycles. Regarding its advantages, it can make full use of the bicycle stagnation caused by the rapid economic development of the city, and maximize the utilization of public road passing rate.

Although the future of bike sharing seems to be prosperous, the whole industry has encountered several questions. For example, the competition of this industry becomes extremely intense with more and more bike sharing companies entering the industry. What is more, the company find it difficult to cultivate the user loyalty, since it makes no difference for users to choose any sharing bikes. Last but not the least, the high operating cost is another problem the bike sharing company has to face.

Many bike sharing companies have already withdrawn from the industry, but there are also companies that survive the winter. We believe that the market for bike sharing is still big. After all, the sharing economy is the inevitable result of social development. We should take warning from those examples and consider how a bike sharing company can create and acquire consumer demands and then make more profit, as a consequence, we have chosen this topic and focus on Mobi to research the methods which help bike sharing companies more profitable. As a Vancouver-based bike sharing company, Mobi was launched in July 2016 in Vancouver and currently has 1500 bicycles with 150 stations in Vancouver. Mobi is still in the dominant status of this industry at present, but it is undeniable that the sky train, uber and taxi could affect citizens’ trip modes. Consequently, our topic will focus on two perspectives to help Mobi solidify its position and gain more customers: the imbalance of sharing bike distributions and the weather effect on bike usage.

Section 2: Data Sources

In order to solve our issue, we have found several datasets after considering the essential factors, which include the bike datasets that we downloaded from data.world and the weather datasets that we obtained from the official Canadian weather website. After comparing these different datasets, we drop out several undetailed datasets which do not conclude enough information, and finally choose Mobi 2018 dataset and the Vancouver weather dataset of 2018.

The reason why we choose Mobi 2018 is that firstly, the target biking sharing company that we mainly focus is Mobi, due to that Mobi is not only located in Vancouver where we are living and familiar with, but also it has the largest bike sharing users. Furthermore, the weather dataset that we have chosen is provided by the Canadian government, which is a reliable resource and thus, would be suitable for our topic.

For the data-set, the link are provided below as the website does not allow the files to be downloaded directly.

  1. Weather Data Set: https://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?StationID=51442&timeframe=2&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2019&Day=3&Year=2018&Month=10#
  2. Bike Data Set: https://data.world/michellecho/vancouver-bike-sharing-2018

For the first combination, we could only combine the data from M1 to M11, since the way in which the date is encoded in the data set for M12 is slightly different. For M1 - M11, date is in the ‘MM/DD/YYYY’ format, while M12 is in ‘YYYY-MM-DD’ format. To correct for this different, we split the date time into three columns for day, month, year with an additional column for hour of departure and return in a day. Once date has been correct, we join the M12 data set with the M1 to M11 to form an entire 2018 bike data-set.

Running some basic summary statistics of the data set shows that there is a significant outliers in the duration and time columns. At the maximum, the data shows 481,050 kilometers biked and 1,752,699 seconds, which is most likely a result of coding errors. Instead, to correct for this, we drop the rows with the top and bottom 1% in the data set (as well as eliminated rows with zero entries for time or distance). Since more than 1% of the sample has their distance travelled at 0, we choose to set the lower boundary of distance travelled at 0 instead of 1% value.

dist_tpct = sort(mobi2018$dist, decreasing = TRUE)[round(length(mobi2018$dist)*.01,0)]
dist_bpct = sort(mobi2018$dist, decreasing = TRUE)[round(length(mobi2018$dist)*.99,0)]
time_tpct = sort(mobi2018$time, decreasing = TRUE)[round(length(mobi2018$time)*.01,0)]
time_bpct = sort(mobi2018$time, decreasing = TRUE)[round(length(mobi2018$time)*.99,0)]


# Dropping top/bottom 1% of time and distance as well as zero entries
mobi2018<-mobi2018[mobi2018$dist < dist_tpct,]
mobi2018<-mobi2018[mobi2018$dist > 0,]
mobi2018<-mobi2018[mobi2018$time < time_tpct,]
mobi2018<-mobi2018[mobi2018$time > time_bpct,]

Lastly, to put the data in first normal form, we then split out the area_id from the name of departing station and returning station, since there will be duplicate stations for all the trips. The station name would then be stored in a separate station table, which is linked to the main data set, using area ID. Lastly, we removed the variable which would not be necessary to our analysis.

Data Cleaning and Processing (Neighborhood)

Using the composite map of all Mobi bike share stations in Vancouver from MountainMath.org, which contains all the current stations of Mobi and their locations as per the figure below.

Figure 2: Station Location

Using neighborhood map from Wikipedia.org, we map each statio to a specific neighborhood. From this we create a data-set which map the stations to eight neighborhoods in Vancouver in which Mobi is operating. These includes:

  1. Stanley Park
  2. Westend
  3. Downtown
  4. Downtown Eastside

  6. Mount Pleasant
  7. Fairview
  8. Grandview-Woodland

Figure 3: Vancouver Neighborhood Map

From this we manually created two tables: ‘station’ and ‘neighborhood.’
‘station_id’ maps unique station name to each departing and returning station for a bike trip in the main data-set. ‘neighborhood’ table has unique id for each of Vancouver neighborhood above, which is then mapped to the ‘station’ table, using these area_id. While we are aware that better mapping method exists by using GPD coordinate. We choose this method for its simplicity under the given time constraints.

For the section below, we import that csv files for station and area as data-frame to be pushed into Postgres. To get the station ID in the station table, we extract the first four digit of station name, which matches with station id in the main data set.

station = read.csv(file = "Bike-share Data/Stations.csv",header = TRUE)

Section 5: Data Analysis and Discussion

To address our central questions regarding the profitability of Mobi, we are tackling the problem on two separate angles.

  1. Demand Side: For revenue, we are looking at the frequency in which customers rent Mobi Bike to establish the dimension and areas in high activity is high so that the company would be able to fous their effort in time and places with high demand.

  2. Cost Side: For cost, the main cost we are trying to address is the cost of redistributing bikes to each station. Since the customers of bike-sharing service seldom return the bikes to the same station, this could lead to an shortage of bike in station with high departure rate (eg. residential area) and excess in the stations with high return rate (eg. near public transit). To address this, the company would have to physically redistribute the bikes back to where there is demand. As each move would require manpower, thus incurring cost, studying the pattern of this imbalance will allow the bikes to be redistributed more effectively.

To begin our analysis, we are sending query to postgres to summarize data into smaller chunks for visualization. Since the data in the main data set is in the level of individual bike trip, we are counting the frequencies of departing trips over different time, area dimensions to capture the level of activities.

bikes = dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT account, COUNT(d_station) as trips 
FROM mobi2018 
GROUP BY account
ORDER BY trips DESC; ")

Area = dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT T1.d_station, 
  ROUND(AVG(T1.time)) as duration, 
  T3.area_name 
FROM mobi2018 as T1
  LEFT JOIN (SELECT * FROM station) as T2 ON T1.d_station = T2.station_name 
  LEFT JOIN (SELECT area_ID, area_name FROM neighborhood) as T3 ON T2.area_id = T3.area_id 
WHERE area_name IS NOT NULL AND d_station IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY T1.d_station, T3.area_name ;")

freq_Area = dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT T1.d_station, 
  COUNT(*) as frequency, 
  T3.area_name 
FROM mobi2018 as T1
  LEFT JOIN (SELECT * FROM station) as T2 ON T1.d_station = T2.station_name 
  LEFT JOIN (SELECT area_ID, area_name FROM neighborhood) as T3 ON  T2.area_id = T3.area_id
WHERE area_name IS NOT NULL AND d_station IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY T1.d_station, T3.area_name;")


duration_hour =  dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT dep_hour, ROUND(AVG(time)) as duration 
FROM mobi2018 
GROUP BY dep_hour;")

freq_hour = dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT dep_hour, COUNT(d_station) as frequency 
FROM mobi2018 
GROUP BY dep_hour;")

freq_weather = dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT T1.num_dep, 
  T2.num_ret, 
  (T1.num_dep - T2.num_ret) as imbalance, 
  dep_month, 
  dep_day, 
  ret_month, 
  max_temp, 
  min_temp, 
  mean_temp, 
  rain_mm, 
  gust 
FROM (SELECT dep_month, dep_day, COUNT(*) as num_dep FROM mobi2018 GROUP BY dep_month, dep_day) as T1 
  INNER JOIN (SELECT ret_month, ret_day, COUNT(*) as num_ret FROM mobi2018 GROUP BY          ret_month, ret_day) as T2 ON dep_month = ret_month AND dep_day = ret_day
  INNER JOIN (SELECT day, month, year, max_temp, min_temp, mean_temp, rain_mm, gust FROM     weather) as T3 ON T1.dep_day = T3.day AND T1.dep_month = T3.month 
ORDER BY imbalance DESC")

imb_Area_new = dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT SUM(T1.num_dep) as num_dep, 
  SUM(T2.num_ret) as num_ret, 
  (SUM(T1.num_dep) - SUM(T2.num_ret)) as imbalance, 
  area_name
FROM (SELECT d_station, COUNT(*) as num_dep FROM mobi2018 GROUP BY d_station) as T1 
  INNER JOIN (SELECT r_station, COUNT(*) as num_ret FROM mobi2018 GROUP BY r_station) as T2   ON d_station = r_station
  INNER JOIN (SELECT station_name,area_id FROM station) as T3 ON d_station = station_name
  INNER JOIN (SELECT area_name,area_id FROM neighborhood) as T4 ON T3.area_id = T4.area_id
WHERE area_name IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY area_name
ORDER BY imbalance DESC;") 

freq_rain  = dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT ROUND(AVG(T1.num_dep)) as avg_dep, 
    ROUND(AVG(T2.num_ret))as avg_ret, 
    ROUND(AVG(duration)) as avg_duration, 
    ROUND(AVG(mean_temp)) as avg_temp, 
    ROUND(AVG(rain_mm)) as avg_rain, 
    T3.rainlevel 
FROM (SELECT dep_month, dep_day, COUNT(*) as num_dep, AVG(time) as duration FROM mobi2018 GROUP BY dep_month, dep_day) as T1 
  INNER JOIN (SELECT ret_month, ret_day, COUNT(*) as num_ret FROM mobi2018 GROUP BY          ret_month, ret_day) as T2 
  ON dep_month = ret_month AND dep_day = ret_day
  INNER JOIN (SELECT day, month, year, max_temp, min_temp, mean_temp, rain_mm, gust,         rainlevel FROM weather) as T3 ON T1.dep_day = T3.day AND T1.dep_month = T3.month 
WHERE rainlevel IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY T3.rainlevel
ORDER BY rainlevel DESC
")

From this graph, we could conclude that the largest duration happens in Stanley Park which has the lowest number of bike stations and the lowest duration happens in Downtown eastside. In addition, the average duration among all stations except Stanley Park is similar. From this perspective, we recommend that Mobi should put more riding bikes to gain more profits.

This graph is about area versus imbalance. To calculate imbalance, we use # of bikes departed from an area minus # of bikes get returned to this area. For example, Downtown has the imbalance at around -14000, it means throughout the whole year, there are total 14000 more bikes are returned to this area than departed. Whereas, in Westend, there are roughly 12,000 bikes being departed more than return.

Although this information has no relationship with customers and usage, it is essential for company to reduce the cost of bike arrangement. Since these two areas are neighbor, the analysis seems to indicate that in terms of redistribution, the company can focus the distribution route between Downtown and Westend instead of running overall the operating area.
In addition, By knowing which areas are expected to need more bikes and which areas need less, we can arrange the bike more efficiently at the very beginning so that to avoid any unnecessary costs later.

Section 6: Conclusion

Using data on usage of Mobi Bike-share in 2018, we analyzed the pattern of bike usage under different time periods and areas. We identified the frequency of the usage as a factor affecting Mobi’s revenue and the difference between the departing and returning bike at any station as a factor affecting Mobi’s cost, since the bike would have to be physically moved back to the station with high departure rate. Lastly, We’ve added an additional data on weather to further refine our analysis to include the effect of temperature and rainfall on frequency of bike sharing.

Based on our analysis, we have found that weather, daytime and month, which have important effects on the bike usage, are three main influencing factors. From the perspective of weather, the number of bike usage has a positive correlation with the temperature of the weather which is intuitively reasonable. People would like to have a ride on a sunny day, as a result, it’s a wise strategy for Mobi to have a weather forecast and prepare a proper number of bike arrangement in advance. Daytime is another important factor that influences the usage of bikes. From the graph above, we could conclude that the rush hour of bike riding is from 10 am to 8 pm, which means that if Mobi could have an appropriate strategy for bike distribution, it is more possible to gain more profits. From the angle of month, it is readily to conclude that people are more likely to have a ride in summer than in winter, which we could also obtain a conclusion from the factor of weather. As a consequence, it would be more profitable for Mobi to adjust their staff in different seasons.

Based on our analysis we recommend Mobi to take into account the weather conditions when adjusting the number of staff, since bike usage decreases rapidly by increasing the amount of rain and decreasing temperature. We also suggest Mobi to have more staff to work in July and Aug since the usage of bikes in these two months is high. On the other hand, during Dec-Feb Mobi does not need as many staff as summer, since the demand for bike sharing is lower than summer.

When analyzing the number of bikes have been taken from and returned to different stations, we found that there exists some imbalance. Hence, to avoid the situation where the people who want to get a bike facing an empty station and people who want to return the bike facing a fully loaded station, Mobi would have to invest in redistributing these bikes back. By analyzing the imbalance, we can suggest Mobi to make a wiser decision when distributing the bikes to avoid such situation which are both harmful to the profit and service level of the company.
